SIMPLE: glimmer
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glimmer
<hw>Glim"mer</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Glimmered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Glimmering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to G.
<ets>glimmer</ets> a faint, trembling light, mica, <ets>glimmern</ets>
to glimmer, <ets>glimmen</ets> to shine faintly, glow, Sw.
<ets>glimma</ets>, Dan. <ets>glimre</ets>, D. <ets>glimmen</ets>,
<ets>glimpen</ets>. See <er>Gleam</er> a ray, and cf.
<er>Glimpse</er>.]</ety> <def>To give feeble or scattered rays of light;
to shine faintly; to show a faint, unsteady light; <as>as, the
<ex>glimmering</ex> dawn; a <ex>glimmering</ex> lamp.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The west yet <qex>glimmers</qex> with some streaks of day.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To gleam; to glitter. See <er>Gleam</er>,
<er>Flash</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glimmer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glimmer
<hw>Glim"mer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A faint, unsteady
light; feeble, scattered rays of light; also, a gleam.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Gloss of satin and <qex>glimmer</qex> of pearls.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mica. See <er>Mica</er>.</def>
<rj><au>Woodsward.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Glimmer gowk</b></col>, <cd>an owl.</cd> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Tennyson.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glimmering</ent>⟦br⟧
